The aim, he said, is to have a confident and happy dog entering a competition. His job is to trim and condition the dogs and prepare them physically and mentally. We finish with close to 100 champions a year, he said. The dogs are frequent winners in best of breed and best of show categories. ; McFadden said he handles an average of 20 to 25 dogs at each show and works around 120 shows a year all over the US. ; We make a good living but the overhead is high and the hours long. 